# Terraform Instructions

Apply these conventions when generating or modifying Terraform code.

## File structure (per module)

```
module/
├── main.tf          # Resource definitions
├── variables.tf     # Input variable declarations
├── outputs.tf       # Output declarations
├── versions.tf      # required_providers and terraform block
├── locals.tf        # Local value computations (if needed)
└── README.md        # Module documentation
```

Do not mix resource definitions and variable declarations in the same file.

## versions.tf template

```hcl
terraform {
  required_version = ">= 1.5"
  required_providers {
    azurerm = {
      source  = "hashicorp/azurerm"
      version = "~> 3.0"
    }
    kubernetes = {
      source  = "hashicorp/kubernetes"
      version = "~> 2.0"
    }
  }
}
```

## Variables

Every variable must have:
- `description` — what it is and how it is used
- Specific `type` — never `any`
- `validation {}` block for constrained values

```hcl
variable "environment" {
  type        = string
  description = "Deployment environment: prod, staging, or dev"
  validation {
    condition     = contains(["prod", "staging", "dev"], var.environment)
    error_message = "environment must be prod, staging, or dev"
  }
}

variable "db_password" {
  type        = string
  description = "Database password — load from Key Vault, never hardcode"
  sensitive   = true
}
```

## Outputs

Every output must have `description`. Mark `sensitive = true` for any output containing credentials, connection strings, or keys.

## Naming

Use `locals {}` for name composition — never repeat the same string expression twice:

```hcl
locals {
  prefix = "${var.workload}-${var.environment}-${var.location_short}"
}

resource "azurerm_resource_group" "main" {
  name = "rg-${local.prefix}"
}
```

## Safety rules

- `prevent_destroy = true` on all stateful resources in production configurations (resource groups, key vaults, databases)
- Use `for_each` over `count` for resource collections — especially collections of objects with attributes
- Never use `lifecycle { ignore_changes = all }` — enumerate specific attributes if needed
- Lock file (`.terraform.lock.hcl`) must be committed

## State

```hcl
terraform {
  backend "azurerm" {
    resource_group_name  = "rg-terraform-state-prod"
    storage_account_name = "stterraformstateprod"
    container_name       = "tfstate"
    key                  = "workload-name/prod.tfstate"
  }
}
```

- Separate `key` values per environment — do not share state between prod and non-prod
- Storage account must have versioning enabled and soft delete configured

## Provider configuration

```hcl
provider "azurerm" {
  features {
    key_vault {
      purge_soft_delete_on_destroy    = false  # require explicit purge
      recover_soft_deleted_key_vaults = true
    }
    resource_group {
      prevent_deletion_if_contains_resources = true
    }
  }
}
```

## Security checklist

- No hardcoded values in `.tf` or `.tfvars` files: regions, subscription IDs, tenant IDs, passwords, keys
- All sensitive variable values sourced from Key Vault data sources or pipeline variable groups
- Private endpoints used for PaaS services — no public network access for production resources
- Minimum TLS 1.2 on all storage accounts and web services
